items.description: What a memorable decade! R.E.M. and U2 ascended as world stars, while grunge changed many people's perception of what could top the charts. Pop-punk (Green Day, The Offspring) and Britpop (Oasis, Blur) were born, just as hip-hop was gaining traction on the charts (Jay-Z, Eminem). Many promising hitmakers would go on to have long, healthy careers, while others would never see the 2000s. But they all belong in our collective memory of the 1990's. (Cover: The Notorious B.I.G. - Ready to Die, Bad Boy/WMG)
items.title: Remember...the 1990s

items.description: Ennio Morricone (1928 - 2020) was one of the greatest movie composers of all time. Since 1946, Morricone composed over 500 scores for cinema and television, as well as over 100 classical works. His filmography includes over 70 award-winning films, including iconic movies by Sergio Leone ('A Fistful of Dollars,' 'For a Few Dollars More,' 'The Good, the Bad and the Ugly' and 'Once Upon a Time in the West'), Giuseppe Tornatore ('Cinema Paradiso'), and also major films like 'The Thing,' 'The Mission,' 'The Untouchables,' 'Bugsy,' 'In the Line of Fire' and 'The Hateful Eight' to name a few. Enjoy this playlist with just some of the highlights from his work over the years. (Photo: Rovi)
items.title: Ennio Morricone Essentials

items.description: The top praise and worship songs to bring you peace and renew your soul! (Cover: Equippers Revolution / Photo: Dream, press)
items.title: Praise & Worship

items.description: The 1980s saw metal and hard rock become extremely popular genres. Bands like AC/DC, Iron Maiden, Metallica, Guns N' Roses and Judas Priest became megastars, filling stadiums across the globe and selling millions of records. The decade also saw the development of extreme subgenres like thrash and death metal, and even the early beginnings of black metal. (Cover: Metallica - 'Master of Puppets', Blackened Records)
items.title: 1980s Metal & Hard Rock

items.description: Outspoken firebrands and activists Rage Against the Machine educated masses of heavy-music fans by injecting their Molotov cocktail of rap, hardcore punk, funk and metal with a sobering dose of fiercely polemical, politically charged urgency. Crashing the mainstream in 1992 with “Killing in the Name” — their sonic protest against police brutality and systemic racism — the band planted their flag in the scene with their triple-platinum self-titled debut. Celebrate that landmark hard-rock LP and other explosive tracks from throughout their discography with these Essentials. (Photo and bio: Rovi)
items.title: Rage Against the Machine Essentials

items.description: The 2000s were fantastic for metal and hard rock. A lot of the biggest and most influential bands turned to a more heavy and aggressive sound, which set the stage for the following years. The decade also introduced many inspiring female personalities to the metal audience, which drove the music in great new directions. (Cover: Mastodon - 'Leviathan', Relapse Records)
items.title: 2000s Metal & Hard Rock

items.description: Fender’s Telecaster was the first mass-produced solidbody electric guitar of note, and seven decades later it remains a staple of blues, country, rock, R&B and even jazz. What’s more, the functional, customizable instrument has been a crucial vehicle for the seamless mixing and melding of American genres. (Photo: Felipe Randolfi/Unsplash)
items.title: Musicology: Fender Telecaster
